shotgun too much, and the training requirements of a handgun or AR-15 too great?

Beretta CX-4 "Storm" 9mm Carbine

links for more info

- Beretta: http://www.berettausa.com/products/cx4-storm/
- Wikipedia: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beretta_Cx4_Storm
- YouTube videos: http://www.youtube.com/channel/HCNc6GeNUYN0E
- Internet Movie Firearms Data Base (IMFDB) http://www.imfdb.org/wiki/Beretta_Cx4_Storm

And here's a 4-part series by Brent Yamamoto that's worth reading if you are interested in this:

http://www.warriortalknews.com/2013/01/snow-storm-the-beretta-cx4.html
http://www.warriortalknews.com/2013/01/snow-storm-part-two.html
http://www.warriortalknews.com/2013/01/snow-storm-part-three.html
http://www.warriortalknews.com/2013/01/beretta-storm-part-four.html

Much has been written about the benefits of PCCs [ pistol caliber carbines ]. Here is a quick summary of why the PCC excels for close contact fighting indoors, and why in my opinion, it's the best overall weapon for home defense:

Muzzle blast - Whether you stick with the stock configuration of a
16 inch barrel, or shorten the barrel length after getting your SBR
approval (which you should do if your state allows that), the muzzle
blast from a PCC just doesn’t compare to a rifle/shotgun. "Tame" is
an understatement. I'll trade the devastation of a shotgun blast for
retaining my night vision in the fight.

Noise - It's inconvenient to lose your hearing during a fight.
Firing a rifle/shotgun indoors is something best avoided if you can
help it. If your hearing isn't important, so be it...but the ability
for you and your family to hear and communicate over the roar of
shotgun fire might come in handy. If you don't have the opportunity
to compare the sound of shotgun/rifle/PCC/pistols indoors, shoot them
side-by-side outdoors. It's not at all the same but it will give you
some idea. In class I've found that PCCs seem tame even next to
suppressed AKs.

Ease of use - In my opinion, a PCC is easier to shoot than any
other platform, pistols included. This is especially true for other
family members. The Storm in particular is a very light weapon. It's
handy and compact, soft shooting and very gentle to handle. As much
as I appreciate the therapeutic properties of the rough edges of an
AK, not everyone in my family does. Easier on the hands and body is a
shooting and fighting benefit for most people. I would not hand my
mom a Remington 870 if I could help it. But a Berretta Storm? You
bet. I'd give it to her, get a beer, and watch the fun.

Recoil - Virtually non-existent when compared to shotguns and many
rifles. Easier to get multiple rounds on target. Low recoil also
helps with...

Accuracy - The low recoil in conjunction with the additional
points of contact on the stock make the PCC a very accurate platform.
In terms of accuracy, anything you can do with a pistol, you can do
easier with a PCC. The strength of the pistol is its small size and
concealability, which is not an issue with a bedside gun. Accuracy
indoors is also easier than a rifle in my opinion, given the points
mentioned above.

Fun - This is a serious consideration in my opinion. Something
that's fun to shoot will get more training time, and more training
time equals more proficiency. Maybe you prefer shooting a 12 gauge
870 to a PCC...but does your wife? Your kids?

MidwayUSA teamed up with Lee Precision to custom design a cast bullet that would not only function from a suppressed AR-15 in 300 AAC Blackout subsonicly, but would not have problems feeding from a magazine and stabilize with the fast twist barrels. REDACTED

The PF-9 is manufactured in Cocoa, Florida by Kel-Tec CNC Industries. Featuring extensive use of CNC (Computer Numerical Control) manufacturing techniques, its six main components consist of the barrel, slide, frame, grip, trigger group, and magazine. The barrel is manufactured of AISA 4140 steel hardened to 48 RHC, and the slide is constructed of the same steel. The frame, which houses the trigger group, consists of a solid machined 7075-T56 aluminum billet. A transfer bar system connects the hammer and trigger. A hammer block safety is incorporated which helps prevent accidental discharge if the pistol is dropped. The long double-action-only trigger pull provides an additional safety feature. The pistol includes a slide hold-open feature which locks the slide in its rearmost position after the last round is fired. The grip is made of DuPont ST-8018 polymer and holds the steel, 7-round, single-column magazine.[3] The sights consist of a fixed front blade and a windage-adjustable notched rear sight. Three white dots highlight the sights for optimum visibility in low-light conditions.
The PF-9 uses many parts originally designed for Kel-Tec’s P11 and P3AT models, and is in fact a compromise between those pistols. From the P11, the PF-9 uses a slightly modified barrel, trigger, ejector, and front sight. The P3AT parts used in the PF-9 include the extractor and various springs. The grip is available in a variety of colors, while the slide is available in blued, Parkerized, ceramic (Cerakote), and hard chromed finishes. The PF-9 is shipped with an extended magazine floorplate, an allen wrench for adjusting the rear sight, and an owner's manual.

title: For Sale:  Custom AR
postcontent:
A quick tutorial on Arms List dot Com verbiage.

"Custom" = put together with gun show junk parts

"Custom Paint" = Spray paint and some leaves from Outside

"Loaded" = every piece of NC Star gear that can possibly fit on any weapon

"Rare"    = there are about 10-15 of them at Sportsman's Warehouse.

"NIB"     = been finger fucked every day for the last few months

"Tactical Shotgun" = Normal Shotgun with a Pistol Grip

"Never Been Fired" = bought for the sole purpose of being resold for more money

"Hard to Find Ammo" = it's Hard to Find because Assholes like the sellers are buying it all up only to sell it for a profit

"I have plenty of Ammo" = I have no job or life, so I sit outside Sportsman's and Wal-Mart everyday and buy it all before you can

"Last Box of 22lr Ammo" = I have 50 more boxes I got from Wal-Mart , and Dick's, and will post a new add tomorrow

"Price Firm" = I am delusional, and want bags of money for my Used gun

"Made in Italy" = I am hoping you know nothing about guns and will think I am selling you something special

"Get it Before the Gub'mint Takes Them" = kooks that bury ammo in their yard and horde cans of soup and batteries

"Please Don't Waste My Time" = I am a douche bag, and have already been told by the Arms List Community many times before.

"Willing to Trade, Let Me Know" = I will only trade my stock Ruger 10/22 for a Solid Gold Anti-Tank cannon and $10,000 from you. 

"Please no Black Powders or Non Gun Items" = Open to Pit Bull Puppies, Flea Market Gold Chains, and Guitar Amps 

I have worked at gun stores in Alaska, Texas, and Colorado. This site makes me smile on a daily basis. Have a good one guys.

title: For Sale:  Walther P99 QA 9mm - Must Sell ASAP!
postcontent:
Must Sell ASAP - Or will trade in for the $400.  Basically, I would rather sell this to someone for a good price than trade it in.  Have to pick up new gun on hold by Friday.

For Sale:  Walther P99 QA 9mm  

Original case, parts, cleaning rod, manuals, and manuafacturer's target and brass shell all are included.
* 2 - 15 round magazines
* 3 backstraps to adjust grip size
* 4 removable front elevation sights at different heights
* Trigger lock

What does the QA mean?  I had to order this particular model when I bought it because I wanted this functionality:

(From the Walther manual)  "The Quick Action (QA) Trigger of the P99QA differs from the standard P99 by offering a constant trigger pull for every round fired.  If you pull the slide rearward and release, with a loaded magazine in the well, the gun will be laded and ready to fire.  Once loaded, pulling the trigger will move the striker to the rear and allow discharge.  Depressing the take down button will decock the gun and render it unable to shoot.  With the striker decocked, the gun will not fire when squeezing the trigger.  If the slide is slightly moved rearward on a decocked gun it will go into a ready to fire mode."

title: For Sale:  Principals of our United States of America
postcontent:
To start, I don't deal much on Armslist but find it interesting to see what is available. I avoid the high priced ammo, like most smarter folk. However, I do have to admit that I am concerned about the listing below, as this person is really trying to incite some bad shizzle.

While I agree that gouging is despicable, what this person is suggesting is really counter to many of the principals we all stand for:

- Creating a registry of "offenders" - seriously?
- Who decides what "gouging" is? This person? Should we include many of the dealers at gun shows selling their ammo for more than usual? These, that many of us call our friends?
- It is one of the conditions of the free market - to allow people to TRY to sell ammo at ridiculous prices and find no one will buy it, WITHOUT regulation. 

However, also in a free market, you can look to OTHER sources, such as MGO, Facebook groups, etc. where those groups can decide whether to monitor or not what is "gouging". Armslist is not the only place to look. 

On Gunbroker.com, you will find that ammo is selling at a much more reasonable rate than the gougers on Armslist. 

If this person is so concerned with price gouging and posts almost every day, good for him. However, to suggest the course of actions he has, he must be a liberal. And have nothing better to do. I can respect taking a stand, however not at the cost of our liberty.

Don't bother replying to this post. I just wanted to share my concern and created a fake email that will not be used again.

Please "Spam/Inappropriate" the following post if you agree. And you are welcome to disagree with me to. That is the beauty of the country we live in.

-----------------------------------------------
RE: FOR SALE: LIST OF GOUGERS

"Due to the current state of gouging I think that an email or phone number list of these fine people ought to be listed(maybe even a pic). So any of you with this information why not share it. Maybe if they get enough angry calls or are bothered enough we can prevent these low life jobless rip offs from running out at all hours of the day and night to buy it all up and try to resell it to us, then those of us who actually shoot and use ammo can get it. Certainly not advocating any sort of violence or anything like that, but ripoffs tend to stop when there outed. Thanks and have a nice day."

title: For Sale:  Chiappa 1911 - 22 LR AWC Valkyrie TI 22 Suppressor
postcontent:
CHIAPPA 1911-22

The Chiappa 1911-22 model is a rimfire, semi-automatic pistol chambered in .22 LR. It is a straight blowback pistol in .22 Long Rifle only, with a fixed barrel solidly attached to the frame.

The Chiappa 1911 is constructed from Chiappalloy and steel components featuring wooden two piece grips. Polymer is used for the magazine catch, mainspring housing, non-rotating grip safety filler, and the body and follower of the 10-round single-column magazine. 

It is the natural choice for semi-auto plinking, target shooting, and affordable handgun fun. Safety features include the traditional left-side thumb safety and a gun lock on the right rear side of the slide. A third safety feature is the gun’s automatic trigger safety, which blocks the trigger until the slide is fully forward into battery. Finally, the hammer features a half-cock notch. The front sight is a fixed sight and has been designed to allow extra material so that it can be filed to adjust for the individual shooter. 

The Chiappa is a fixed barrel blow back design that maintains reliable functioning with minimal friction. The reliable return of the slide in combination w/ fixed front and rear sights maintans a constant return and quick, accurate follow-up shots. It includes two 10-rd magazines.

AWC VALKYRIE TI 22 SUPPRESSOR.

The Valkyrie TI is a super light-weight titanium suppressor. The AWC Valkyrie has an interchangeable rear mounting system, which allows you to swap between multiple host weapons regardless of thread pattern. 

This is AWC's nicest titanium can, and it is made from solid titanium stock; it is not made from titanium tubing like others who use cheaper methods that don't give as nice of a build quality. This AWC model uses a solid welded fully machined blast baffle. It’s forward purging design means gases cool faster while moving forward more efficiently.

The Valkyrie offers unbelievably accurate suppressed shooting. The Valkyrie is far and away the BEST 22 CAN ON THE MARKET and is of course also suited for the 17 HMR and 22 magnum in other firearms. The mounting systems you can change between are (universal): 1/2 x28, 3/8 x24, P22, SIG Mosquito, 3/8 x24 Tang & Custom. Because of the AWC rear mounting system, it is very easy to change the can from one thread pitch to another. Best of all, the AWC Valkyrie never has to be cleaned!

title: For Sale:  Principals of our United States of America
postcontent:
To start, I don't deal much on Armslist but find it interesting to see what is available. I avoid the high priced ammo, like most smarter folk. However, I do have to admit that I am concerned about the listing below, as this person is really trying to incite some bad shizzle.

While I agree that gouging is despicable, what this person is suggesting is really counter to many of the principals we all stand for:

- Creating a registry of "offenders" - seriously?
- Who decides what "gouging" is? This person? Should we include many of the dealers at gun shows selling their ammo for more than usual? These, that many of us call our friends?
- It is one of the conditions of the free market - to allow people to TRY to sell ammo at ridiculous prices and find no one will buy it, WITHOUT regulation. 

However, also in a free market, you can look to OTHER sources, such as MGO, Facebook groups, etc. where those groups can decide whether to monitor or not what is "gouging". Armslist is not the only place to look. 

On Gunbroker.com, you will find that ammo is selling at a much more reasonable rate than the gougers on Armslist. 

If this person is so concerned with price gouging and posts almost every day, good for him. However, to suggest the course of actions he has, he must be a liberal. And have nothing better to do. I can respect taking a stand, however not at the cost of our liberty.

Don't bother sending hate mail. I just wanted to share my concern and created a alias that will not be used again.

Please "Spam/Inappropriate" the following post if you agree. And you are welcome to disagree with me to. That is the beauty of the country we live in.

-----------------------------------------------
RE: FOR SALE: LIST OF GOUGERS

"Due to the current state of gouging I think that an email or phone number list of these fine people ought to be listed(maybe even a pic). So any of you with this information why not share it. Maybe if they get enough angry calls or are bothered enough we can prevent these low life jobless rip offs from running out at all hours of the day and night to buy it all up and try to resell it to us, then those of us who actually shoot and use ammo can get it. Certainly not advocating any sort of violence or anything like that, but ripoffs tend to stop when there outed. Thanks and have a nice day."
